[h1]Blockades[/h1]
Adds a [b]Blockade[/b] default behavior for your fleet, plus an AI system that has the major races set up their own blockades at hostile-facing gates in their territory. Built for X4: Foundations 9.0. No vanilla files modified — drops in next to anything.

[b]⚠ Work-in-progress.[/b] Player blockades and the AI auto-deploy flow are stable in short play sessions; long-running balance, edge cases (sub re-targeting after a gate switches owner, behavior across sector handoffs), and very large wings still need testing in the wild. [b]Please report bugs[/b] — log snippets help most. See [b]Source, issues, and license[/b] below.

[h2]Player usage[/h2]
[olist]
[*]Select a ship or wing.
[*]Open the [b]Behavior[/b] dropdown.
[*]Pick [b]Blockade[/b].
[*]Choose a gate as the target.
[/olist]

The wing leader sits in front of the gate (offset slightly above the highway centerline so capital hulls don't fight mass-traffic). Subordinates fan out in a hemisphere on the hostile side, class-sorted: L/XL ships fill the inner ring closer to the leader, M and S spill out to the middle and outer rings. Capitals anchor, fast hulls intercept.

While the area is quiet the ring sits perfectly still. When an enemy enters [b]Engagement Range[/b] of the gate, the leader dispatches the whole wing with full Attack orders — including L/XL subordinates with their main batteries. Combat is bounded to the engagement area: ships disengage anything that leaves it and fly back to their slots once the area is clear. New arrivals re-trigger the attack immediately, even while ships are still returning. Ships added to the wing mid-blockade are assigned a slot automatically — no need to reissue the order.

The leader is bastion-style: holds position as the formation anchor, turrets fire at anything in range.

[h2]Recommended fleet leader[/h2]
Use an [b]L (destroyer)[/b] or [b]M (frigate / corvette)[/b] as the wing leader. [b]XL pathfinding currently has issues[/b] — XL hulls work fine as subordinates, just not as the leader. [b]Note for L/XL flagships:[/b] the leader's own forward main batteries don't fire automatically (an Attack order would override the blockade itself) — turrets handle leader-side engagement. Subordinate L/XL ships [i]do[/i] use their main batteries.

[h2]Order parameters[/h2]
[list]
[*][b]Distance from Gate[/b] (default 10 km) — radius of the formation sphere.
[*][b]Engagement Range[/b] (default ship's radar range) — hostiles outside this are ignored.
[*][b]Pursue Targets[/b] (advanced) — if on, ships chase beyond the formation. Off by default.
[*][b]Face Away From Gate[/b] — reverse formation orientation; useful for sector-side blockades.
[*][b]Side[/b] (auto) — 0 picks the side from gate type; 1 = destination-facing; -1 = interior-facing.
[*][b]Timeout[/b] (default 0 = infinite).
[/list]

[h2]AI auto-blockade[/h2]
Deployment is handled by X4's [b]job system[/b], not script-spawning. The mod adds per-race blockade jobs for [b]Argon, Paranid, Teladi, Split, Terran, Boron[/b]: an L destroyer leader with 3 M frigate/corvette and 4 S heavy-fighter subordinates per wing. Faction shipyards queue and build these over real time, respecting wares and build slots.

Quotas: up to [b]6 blockade fleets per faction galaxy-wide, max 1 per cluster[/b].

Each spawned leader picks its own hostile-facing gate in its sector and flies the wing into formation. When the hostile relationship ends (relation thaws, gate destroyed, sector changes hands), the order finishes naturally and the job system decides whether to queue a replacement.

[b]Plans are to refine, expand and balance the AI behaviour over time. Let me know what ideas you have![/b]

[h2]Compatibility[/h2]
[list]
[*][b]X4 9.0[/b] required. Older versions are not supported.
[*]All Egosoft DLCs supported (Split, Terran, Pirate, Boron, Timelines).
[*][b]No vanilla diffs[/b] — additive patches only, no replacement of vanilla files. Conflicts with other mods are highly unlikely.
[/list]

[h2]Save-game safety[/h2]
The mod stores state under its own variable namespace; removing it mid-save leaves any spawned blockade ships with an invalid order — they fall back to their previous default behavior and stay in the world. No persistent locks or flags survive uninstall.

